Defendant Terrell D Johnson in court with attorney Anne A. Devitt.  Defendant Terrell D Johnson in custody.  Megan Patricia Carmody appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by State, defense, and defendant. 
 
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of  5 YEARS, CONSECUTIVE to any other time being served with credit for 0 days served. The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 2 YEARS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 3 YEARS.

The defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Substance Abuse Program AFTER SERVING THE FIRST YEAR OF THIS SENTENCE.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
*Obtain Mental health assessment and successfully complete follow-up treatment;
* Take any prescription medication only in the manner/dosage as prescribed by a treating physician;
*Obtain AODA assessment and if necessary successfully complete follow-up treatment;
*Participate with random urine screens;
*No drug dealing or association with drug community (drug users/dealers or drug houses);
*Cooperate with any and all rules set forth by the probation agent;
*No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause;
*No contact with victim Betty B., her family or her residence at 3961 N. 23rd;
*Obtain/maintain full time employment or full time school and part time employment;
*Participate in Cognitive thinking program;
*Obtain GED or HSED;
*Pay all supervision fees;
*Provide DNA sample if not previously done so- pay surcharge;
*Pay all applicable mandatory surcharges, fees, assessments, and costs- paid after restitution; 

The Court ordered restitution at this time in the stipulated amount of $685.73 payable to Betty B.-to be paid first.  Additional restitution request may be forthcoming.  The Court ordered that all financial obligations and restitution be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment.  Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.  Appeal rights given by the court.
